ngeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saint Peter's and Saint Paul's Churchyard, Wincanton, Somersetshire, England ":"Wincanton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"before 1514–Bef 1572":"before 1514–before 1572","1504–1601":"1504–1601","1514–1572":"1514–1572","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1486–1560":"1486–1560","1583":"1583","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","Abt 1539":"about 1539","1490":"1490","before 1514":"before 1514","1525":"1525","1514":"1514","1601":"1601","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","Bef 1572":"before 1572","about 1560":"about 1560","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Saint Peter's and Saint Paul's Churchyard, Wincanton, Somersetshire, England ":"Wincanton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haskell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Askell</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, from Old Norse <i>Áskell</i>, a shortened form of <i>Ásketill</i> (see   Axtell  ). The personal name was also popular among the Normans, sometimes in the form <i>Anskell</i> (with ancient Germanic <i>Ans-</i> substituted for <i>As-</i>), which explains why the name occurs in post-Conquest England in counties not settled by Vikings. Its appearance as a surname is often disguised by altered pronunciations; metathesis of /sk/ to /ks/, spelled <i>-x-</i>, for example, has given rise to   Axtell  . The Normans frequently used the name in Frankish forms; see   Askin  ,   Haskin  ,   Hasty  , and   Astin  . For the name in the Isle of Man see   Castell  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Khaskl</i>, a Yiddish form of the Hebrew name <i>Yeḥezqel</i> (see   Ezekiel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hascall","meanings":["English: variant of   Haskell  ."]},{"name":"Haskel","meanings":["English: variant of   Haskell  ."]},{"name":"Axtell","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Asketill</i>, from Old Norse <i>Ásketill</i>, composed of the elements <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’ (see also   Haskell  ). This name was in use both among Scandinavian settlers in eastern England (esp. Norfolk) and among the Normans.","nickname for a salt merchant or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>hakke-salt</i> ‘chop salt (into pieces)’. The development of the surname to <i>Axtel</i> is evidenced in 16th-century Hertfordshire and Buckinghamshire."]},{"name":"Askin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>Askin</i>, a shortened form of the Norman personal name <i>Asketin</i>, a pet form of <i>Asketill</i>, <i>Askell</i>, which is of Old Norse origin and related to   Haskell  .","English: variant of <b>Askerne</b>, a habitational name from Askern, in Campsall, near Doncaster (Yorkshire). The placename denoted a house (Old English <i>ærn</i>) by an ash tree (Old English <i>æsc</i>, influenced or substituted by Old Norse <i>askr</i>).","English and Irish: variant of   Heskin  ."]},{"name":"Hasty","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Asti</i>, a shortened form of <i>Astin</i>, a pet form of <i>Asketin</i>, derived from Old Norse <i>Ásketill</i>, composed of the elements <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’. Compare   Haskell   and   Astin  .","English: possibly a habitational name from Ashday in Southowram (Yorkshire). The placename may derive from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘eastern, east’ + <i>(ge)hæg</i> ‘enclosure’ or <i>hēah</i> ‘high place’.","Scottish: nickname for a brisk or impetuous person, or possibly for a messenger, from Older Scots <i>hastie</i>, Middle English <i>hasty</i>, <i>hastif</i> ‘speedy, quick’, also ‘impetuous, hot-tempered’ (Old French <i>hastif</i>)."]},{"name":"Heiskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Haskell  ."]},{"name":"Hassell","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Hassall (Cheshire), from Old English <i>hætse</i> ‘witch’ (a shortened form of <i>hægtesse</i>) + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’.","variant of <b>Askell</b>, with metathesis of /sk/ to /ks/ and the addition of prosthetic <i>H-</i>; see   Haskell   and   Axtell  ."]},{"name":"Astin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Astin</i>, a shortened form of <i>Asketin</i>, a diminutive of Old Norse <i>Ásketill</i>, composed of the elements <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>ketill</i> ‘sacrificial cauldron, helmet’ (see   Haskell  ,   Askin  ). There has been some confusion over the years between this surname and others (in particular,   Aspden  ,   Aston  , and   Austin  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Haskell was born before 1514, in Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Haskell, was 24 and his mother, Mary Babson Noble Riggs, was 28. He married Joan Foyle about 1539. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1572, in his hometown, and was buried in Wincanton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1514–Bef 1572":"enne 1514–enne 1572","1504–1601":"1504–1601","1514–1572":"1514–1572","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1486–1560":"1486–1560","1583":"1583","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","Abt 1539":"umbes 1539","1490":"1490","before 1514":"enne 1514","1525":"1525","1514":"1514","1601":"1601","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","Bef 1572":"enne 1572","about 1560":"umbes 1560","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Peter's and Saint Paul's Churchyard, Wincanton, Somersetshire, England ":"Wincanton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"before 1514–Bef 1572":"ennen vuotta 1514–ennen vuotta 1572","1504–1601":"1504–1601","1514–1572":"1514–1572","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1486–1560":"1486–1560","1583":"1583","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","Abt 1539":"noin 1539","1490":"1490","before 1514":"ennen vuotta 1514","1525":"1525","1514":"1514","1601":"1601","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","Bef 1572":"ennen vuotta 1572","about 1560":"noin 1560","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Saint Peter's and Saint Paul's Churchyard, Wincanton, Somersetshire, England ":"Wincanton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"before 1514–Bef 1572":"avant 1514–avant 1572","1504–1601":"1504–1601","1514–1572":"1514–1572","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1540–1575":"1540–1575","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1486–1560":"1486–1560","1583":"1583","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","Abt 1539":"environ 1539","1490":"1490","before 1514":"avant 1514","1525":"1525","1514":"1514","1601":"1601","1542":"1542","1575":"1575","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","Bef 1572":"avant 1572","about 1560":"environ 1560","1504":"1504","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, En